  <refsection><title>Description</title>
    <para>
    Let <literal>C-</literal> stands for the control key. The following keyboard commands are available:
  </para>
    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry><term>C-l</term><listitem>
        <para>clears the Scilab window</para>
      </listitem></varlistentry>
      <varlistentry><term>C-d</term><listitem>
        <para>deletes the current character</para>
      </listitem></varlistentry>
      <varlistentry><term>C-p</term><listitem>
        <para>calls back the preceding command</para>
      </listitem></varlistentry>
      <varlistentry><term>C-n</term><listitem>
        <para>go to next command line</para>
      </listitem></varlistentry>
      <varlistentry><term>C-a</term><listitem>
        <para>moves the cursor to the beginning of command line.</para>
      </listitem></varlistentry>
      <varlistentry><term>C-b</term><listitem>
        <para>backspace, moves the cursor one character to the left</para>
      </listitem></varlistentry>
      <varlistentry><term>C-f</term><listitem>
        <para>forwards, moves the cursor one character to the right</para>
      </listitem></varlistentry>
      <varlistentry><term>C-k</term><listitem>
        <para>kills command line from cursor to the end.</para>
      </listitem></varlistentry>
      <varlistentry><term>C-y</term><listitem>
        <para>yank, retrieves killed line.</para>
      </listitem></varlistentry>
      <varlistentry><term>!beg</term><listitem>
        <para>looks for last command line which begins by <literal>beg</literal>.</para>
      </listitem></varlistentry>
      <varlistentry><term>C-c</term><listitem>
        <para>interrupts Scilab and pause after carriage return. (Only functions can be interrupted). Clicking on the stop button enters a <literal>C-C</literal>.</para>
      </listitem></varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </refsection>
